        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Baltimore</placeName>
                <date>July 22d 1849</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Perceiving from the Occident<lb/> that several congregations are in
                want of Readers or<lb/> Hazans, I may probably be aiding their wishes by<lb/>
                communicating to you that from a letter lately received<lb/> by my Mother from
                    <placeName>England</placeName>, we learn that a brother<lb/> of the
                    <persName>Revd Mr Isaacs</persName> of <placeName>New York</placeName> is about
                visiting the<lb/>
                <placeName>U. States</placeName>, and with a view perhaps to an engage-<lb/>ment as
                Hazan—By way therefore of information<lb/> in such a way as you may deem fit to
                mention it, I<lb/> have extracted that portion of the letter referred to, which<lb/>
                is annexed—I should be gratified should it result<lb/> beneficially to the parties
                interested.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With the best regards of our family, I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Dear sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Yours with great respect</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">Mendes Cohen</persName>
            </p>
            <p>|<hi rend="underline">Over</hi>|</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <hi rend="underline">Extract</hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">“I have now to congratulate you on the proba-<lb/>bility of the
                    <persName>Revd. D. M. Isaacs</persName> going to the
                    <placeName>states</placeName><lb/> he having sent in his resignation as lecturer
                to the<lb/>
                <placeName>Liverpool</placeName> congregation. The reason he has given for so<lb/>
                doing, is the smallness of the salary, which I can<lb/> readily believe for it is
                too trifling for a person of his<lb/> acquirements to receive. Yet disordered as the
                finan-<lb/>cial affairs of the congregation are I fear there are<lb/> other causes
                in operation; such as, their want of appreci-<lb/>ation of him, and the division in
                their councils.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Isaacs</persName> who I believe has a brother who
                lec-<lb/>tures in <placeName>N. York</placeName> has been above 12 years amongst
                us.<lb/> Educated under the auspices and in the house of our late<lb/> chief Rabbi,
                he possesses all the energy and learning<lb/> of that eminent divine combined with
                the elegancies<add>?</add><lb/> of modern literature, and was the first in this
                coun-<lb/>try, who dared to turn aside from the beaten track,<lb/> and enlighten us
                with sermons in the vernacular<lb/> tongue. I shall sincerely regret his
                departure.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">But merit seems to turn to the best to be appre-<lb/>ciated: and I
                have no doubt he will be eagerly<lb/> sought after in the
                    <placeName>States</placeName>.”</p>
